hat counted as evidence in court, the battleground of slavery lay in who could speak and under what conditions. But, as Ogborn shows through keen attention to both the traces of talk and the silences in the archives, if enslavement as a legal status could be made by words, it could be unmade by them as well. A deft interrogation of the duality of domination, The Freedom of Speech offers a rich interpretation of oral cultures that both supported and constantly threatened to undermine the slave system.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aFreedom of speechzBarbados. 0aFreedom of speechzJamaica. 0aOral communicationzBarbados. 0aOral communicationzJamaica. 0aSlaveryzBarbadosxHistory. 0aSlaveryzJamaicaxHistory. 0aSlaveszBarbadosxSocial conditions. 0aSlaveszJamaicaxSocial conditions. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aAtlantic world.  aBarbados.  aJamaica.  aabolition.  aglobal history.  ahistorical geography.  aimperial history.  aobeah.  aslavery.  aspeech.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019z9783110664232oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2019 Englishz978311061017808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2019z9783110606195oZDB-23-DEG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311071194340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226657714423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226657714/original  a978-3-11-061017-8  EBOOK PACKAGE History 2019 Englishb2019  a978-3-11-061076-5  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishb2019  a978-3-11-071194-3  University of Chicago Press Complete